            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('Instagram', size: 32) %>
              <span>Instagram</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('YouTube', size: 32) %>
              <span>YouTube</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('TikTok', size: 32) %>
              <span>TikTok</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('BlueSky', size: 32) %>
              <span>BlueSky</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-4">Additional Platforms</h3>
          <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('TruthSocial', size: 32) %>
              <span>Truth Social</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('Gettr', size: 32) %>
              <span>Gettr</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('Rumble', size: 32) %>
              <span>Rumble</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('Telegram', size: 32) %>
              <span>Telegram</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-gray-700">
              <%= platform_icon('Threads', size: 32) %>
              <span>Threads</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-4">
            Platform coverage evolves as new platforms emerge and others decline.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Account Types</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
          Political figures frequently maintain multiple accounts on each platform for different purposes. We distinguish between three channel types:
        </p>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-200">
            <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 mb-1">Campaign</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Accounts used for electoral campaigning and political messaging. This is the primary focus of our initial data collection.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-200">
            <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 mb-1">Official Office</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Government-issued accounts used in an official capacity (e.g., @POTUS, @SenatorSmith).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-200">
            <div class="font-medium text-gray-900 mb-1">Personal</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Private accounts that may also contain political content but are not maintained in an official or campaign capacity.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Data Model -->
    <section class="py-8">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200 p-8">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">How the Data Is Structured</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 mb-10">
          CandiData's data model is designed to capture the full complexity of American political life: people hold multiple offices over time, run in elections, change party affiliations, and maintain social media accounts across many platforms.
        </p>

      <!-- ER Diagram (text-based) -->
      <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-8 mb-10 overflow-x-auto">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-6 text-center">Entity Relationship Overview</h3>
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center gap-2 text-sm font-mono text-gray-700 min-w-[600px]">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 justify-center flex-wrap">
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-purple-100 text-purple-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Party</span>
            <span class="text-gray-400">&larr; many-to-many &rarr;</span>
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-indigo-100 text-indigo-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Person</span>
            <span class="text-gray-400">&larr; many-to-many &rarr;</span>
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-blue-100 text-blue-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Office</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-8 justify-center text-gray-400 my-1">
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span>&darr;</span>
            <span></span>
            <span>&darr;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 justify-center flex-wrap">
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-pink-100 text-pink-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Social Media Account</span>
            <span class="text-gray-400">&larr; belongs to</span>
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-indigo-100 text-indigo-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Person</span>
            <span class="text-gray-400">runs in &rarr;</span>
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-amber-100 text-amber-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Contest</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-8 justify-center text-gray-400 my-1">
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span>&darr;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 justify-center flex-wrap">
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-blue-100 text-blue-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Office</span>
            <span class="text-gray-400">&larr; belongs to</span>
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-teal-100 text-teal-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Body</span>
            <span class="text-gray-400 ml-8">Contest &isin;</span>
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-orange-100 text-orange-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">Ballot</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-8 justify-center text-gray-400 my-1">
            <span>&darr;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 justify-center">
            <span class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-green-100 text-green-800 rounded-lg font-semibold">District</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-4">People &amp; Political Identity</h3>
          <dl class="space-y-4">
            <div>
              <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Person</dt>
              <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">The central record. Contains biographical data (name, gender, state of residence, websites) and links to everything else. A person can be an officeholder, a candidate, or both.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Party</dt>
              <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">Political parties (58 tracked, from major to minor and territory-specific). People can have multiple party affiliations with one marked as primary &mdash; important for states with fusion voting like New York.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Social Media Account</dt>
              <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">A single account on a single platform for a single person, categorized by channel type (Campaign, Official, Personal). Tracks URL, handle, verification status, and which researcher entered and verified the data.</dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-4">Government Structure</h3>
          <dl class="space-y-4">
            <div>
              <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Body</dt>
              <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">A legislative body or governing council (e.g., U.S. Senate, TX State House, Cook County Board). Bodies have a level (federal, state, local), branch, and chamber type.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Office</dt>
              <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">A specific seat within a body or independent position (e.g., U.S. Senator from Texas, Governor of California). Categorized by level, branch, and role.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">District</dt>
              <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">An electoral or administrative boundary. Includes congressional districts, state senate districts, state house districts, and local wards. Linked to offices via OCD-IDs (Open Civic Data Identifiers).</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Officeholder</dt>
              <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">The temporal link between a Person and an Office &mdash; with start date, end date, and whether the position was elected or appointed. Enables tracking who held what office and when.</dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-4">Elections</h3>
        <dl class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
          <div>
            <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Ballot</dt>
            <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">An election event in a specific state on a specific date (e.g., "2024 Texas Republican Primary"). Groups related contests together.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Contest</dt>
            <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">A single race on a ballot for a specific office (e.g., "2024 TX-22 Republican Primary"). Records the date, type, and party.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt class="font-medium text-gray-900">Candidate</dt>
            <dd class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-1">A person's participation in a contest. Tracks outcome (won, lost, pending, withdrawn), vote tally, incumbency status, and party at time of candidacy.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Why It's Designed This Way -->
    <section class="py-8">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200 p-8">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Design Principles</h2>

      <div class="space-y-8">
        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-indigo-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-indigo-600 font-bold text-lg mt-1">1</div>
          <div class="flex-1">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Temporal Accuracy</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600">
              Politicians change offices, switch parties, and create new social media accounts over time. Rather than storing a single snapshot, CandiData records officeholder terms with start and end dates, candidate records per election cycle, and party affiliations as a many-to-many relationship. This means we can answer questions like "Who held this seat in 2020?" or "Which candidates ran in the 2024 primaries?" without losing historical context.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-indigo-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-indigo-600 font-bold text-lg mt-1">2</div>
          <div class="flex-1">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Human Verification</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600">
              Automated scraping of social media accounts produces unreliable results &mdash; impersonation accounts, outdated handles, and misattributed pages are common. CandiData uses a structured research and verification workflow where every social media account is entered by a trained researcher and independently verified by a second person. This two-step process ensures high data quality at the cost of speed, a trade-off we consider essential for research integrity.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-indigo-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-indigo-600 font-bold text-lg mt-1">3</div>
          <div class="flex-1">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Full Government Coverage</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600">
              Most political data projects focus exclusively on Congress. CandiData covers all levels &mdash; federal, state, and local &mdash; because algorithmic transparency research must account for the full landscape of political speech online. A state legislator's Facebook page is subject to the same algorithmic decisions as a U.S. Senator's, and researchers need both.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-indigo-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-indigo-600 font-bold text-lg mt-1">4</div>
          <div class="flex-1">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Platform Breadth</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600">
              Political speech is no longer confined to mainstream platforms. CandiData tracks 11 platforms including emerging and alternative networks like BlueSky, Truth Social, Gettr, Rumble, and Telegram. As new platforms gain political significance, they are added to our tracking scope.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-indigo-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-indigo-600 font-bold text-lg mt-1">5</div>
          <div class="flex-1">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Provenance &amp; Audit Trail</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600">
              Every change to the database is tracked. We record which researcher entered each social media account, which verifier confirmed it, and when. The system maintains a full version history of changes to people, assignments, and account records, providing a transparent chain of custody for every data point.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Research Workflow -->
    <section class="py-8">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200 p-8">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">The Research Process</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 mb-10">
          Data quality is the foundation of meaningful research. Every record in CandiData passes through a structured, multi-stage workflow.
        </p>

      <!-- Step 1: Data Ingestion -->
      <div class="relative">
        <div class="space-y-8">
          <div class="flex gap-6 mb-12">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center">
              <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg">1</div>
              <div class="w-0.5 flex-1 bg-gray-200 mt-4 mb-12"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Data Ingestion &amp; Seeding</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                We begin by importing authoritative reference data from multiple public sources to establish the universe of elected officials and candidates.
              </p>
              <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <div class="font-medium text-blue-900 mb-1">GovProj / BallotInfo</div>
                  <p class="text-sm text-blue-700">42,780 current officeholders across all levels of government, with office details, contact info, and term dates.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <div class="font-medium text-blue-900 mb-1">Election Records</div>
                  <p class="text-sm text-blue-700">17,900+ candidate records from federal and state elections, including outcomes and vote tallies.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <div class="font-medium text-blue-900 mb-1">Existing Social Media Data</div>
                  <p class="text-sm text-blue-700">66,000+ previously collected social media account records that serve as a starting point for verification.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <div class="font-medium text-blue-900 mb-1">Open Civic Data</div>
                  <p class="text-sm text-blue-700">Standardized identifiers (OCD-IDs) for offices, districts, and jurisdictions enable cross-referencing.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Step 2: Assignment -->
