            <div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center">
              <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-indigo-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg">2</div>
              <div class="w-0.5 flex-1 bg-gray-200 mt-4 mb-12"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Assignment &amp; Data Collection</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                An administrator assigns individual politicians to researchers for data collection. When an assignment is created, the system pre-populates placeholder records for each core platform (Facebook, Twitter/X, Instagram, YouTube, TikTok, BlueSky), creating a structured checklist.
              </p>
              <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                The researcher then works through each platform, searching for the politician's official campaign account. For each platform, the researcher either:
              </p>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-600">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="mt-1 w-5 h-5 bg-green-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0"><span class="text-green-600 text-xs font-bold">&#10003;</span></span>
                  <span><strong class="text-gray-900">Enters the account</strong> &mdash; providing the URL and/or handle, then confirming they verified the account exists on the platform and via Google search.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="mt-1 w-5 h-5 bg-gray-200 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0"><span class="text-gray-500 text-xs font-bold">&times;</span></span>
                  <span><strong class="text-gray-900">Marks it as not found</strong> &mdash; indicating they searched and determined the politician does not have a campaign account on that platform.</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-gray-600 mt-4">
                Researchers can attach notes to any account record to document edge cases, ambiguous situations, or additional context for the verifier.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Step 3: Verification -->
          <div class="flex gap-6 mb-12">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center">
              <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg">3</div>
              <div class="w-0.5 flex-1 bg-gray-200 mt-4 mb-12"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Independent Verification</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                Once a researcher completes their assignment, the person's accounts enter the verification queue. A different researcher &mdash; acting as a verifier &mdash; independently reviews each account record. They can see the researcher's entries and notes, but must independently confirm accuracy.
              </p>
              <p class="text-gray-600">
                For each account, the verifier either <strong class="text-gray-900">verifies</strong> the entry (confirming it is correct) or <strong class="text-gray-900">rejects</strong> it with notes explaining the issue. Rejected accounts are flagged for correction.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Step 4: Publication -->
          <div class="flex gap-6">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center">
              <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-amber-500 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg">4</div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Quality Assurance &amp; Publication</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
                Verified accounts are marked as confirmed in the database with a timestamp and the identity of the verifier. Administrators have a global view of all assignments, account statuses, and research progress, enabling them to monitor data quality and reassign work as needed.
              </p>
              <p class="text-gray-600">
                The resulting dataset &mdash; with every account traced to a researcher and verifier &mdash; forms a reliable foundation for downstream social listening and algorithmic transparency research.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

